rlm-jira-pick

Pick a JIRA issue via fzf and open it in the browser. The picker shows
every issue you currently care about, grouped and color-coded by why it
matters to you:

  1. assigned — issues assigned to you (yellow)
  2. reporter — issues you reported, but are assigned to someone else
                (green)
  3. watching — issues you watch, but neither assigned to you nor
                reported by you (cyan)
  4. DATA     — every other issue in the DATA project (magenta)

Within each group, issues are sorted by most recently updated first.
Groups are concatenated in the order above. A picker pick is also
remembered and floats to the top on subsequent invocations (MRU
history kept in ~/.cache/jira-pick/history.txt; cap 1000 lines), with
its original group coloring preserved.

The first line of the picker is "--- REFRESH CACHE (cached … ago)".
Picking it deletes the items cache and re-runs the four JQL queries.
History survives the refresh.

Every invocation verifies that `acli jira auth status` succeeds. If
not, the function transparently runs `acli jira auth login --web`
before continuing.

KEY BINDINGS
  Enter      Open the picked issue at
             https://storytel.atlassian.net/browse/<KEY>
  Ctrl-P     Cycle preview pane height: tall (70%) → short (40%) →
             hidden → tall
  Escape     Cancel

CACHE
  ~/.cache/jira-pick/items.tsv    fetched issue list (tab-delimited)
  ~/.cache/jira-pick/history.txt  MRU picks (one KEY per line)

REQUIRES
  acli, fzf, python3, open (macOS) or xdg-open (Linux).
